2 🌟 The girl who made me mama. 

Today did not turn out the way we planned. Something unexpected (🦠) forced us to abandon our birthday plans and we had to stay home instead.  At first I was irrationally devastated. After a tough pregnancy and emotional post partum period, I really wanted to give Kennedy the special day she deserves.

We spent the day laughing, playing with play dough, pretending to be baristas, cuddling under blankets on the couch while watching Moana, and eating all her favorite snacks. 

To me, this didn’t seem good enough until the end of the day when I realized not one tantrum was had and we spent more time together just the two of us than we have in the past 9 months. It wasn’t the day I planned, but it was still a good day. 

 I know that she is still so young and may not fully understand birthdays, but today I once again was blown away by the resiliency of children. 

Enjoy some blurry photos of our day and some recent favorites 💜 happy birthday, K.

#motherhoodunplugged #motherhoodjourney #motherhoodsimplified #motherhoodmoments #honestmotherhood #reallifemoments

Our March Books ☘️🌈 

Spring is my least favorite season in NY - it basically doesn’t start until May. I made an effort to *try* to enjoy it a tiny bit more by finding some fun books about spring weather for K and I to read this month. We also picked out books about rainbows and St. Patrick’s Day! 

K’s favorite so far is How the Crayons Saved the Rainbow 🌈 a book about crayons working together to help the sun and clouds bring color back to the sky 💜 a great story about teamwork and perseverance

My favorite is Almost Time, which is a sweet book about a boy patiently waiting for the trees to be ready to be tapped for maple syrup, which seemed weather appropriate for us here! 

Full list posted in stories and on my Amazon storefront!

TGIF ☀️📚🏖️ Earlier in the week I shared my recommendations for your summer reading list. Swipe to see what I am hoping to read this summer! Considering I have read only slightly more than what is on this list so far this year, it’s a little ambitious, but I couldn’t narrow it down! I feel like I have a good mix of genres, a little heavier on the light & fun beach reads 💜 What books are on the top of your list this summer? Anything I should add??
HFD to our number 1 💜🥰

⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️ 5/5 (fantasy, romantasy) 

What can I say about this book that hasn’t been said all over social media. It has everything that I could possibly ask for in a fantasy novel 

- a bada$$ female heroine who rises to the occasion when the odds are stacked against her
- A brooding male anti hero (enemies to lovers, which say no more) 
- An academic magical setting 📚 
- Dragons 🐉 
- Female friendship
- Family drama
- So much ACTION
- A crazy jaw dropping twist of events

If you are a fantasy reader, you probably have already read this. If not, and you are looking to give this genre a try this is a FANTASTIC choice. The world building is not overwhelming and super easy to follow. 

The story is set in the magical world of Navarre at a war college where young adults learn a vocation to contribute to their nation.  You can become a scribe, healer or the most dangerous of all, dragon rider. Our main character Violet has trained to become a scribe her whole life but is ordered by her mother to follow the family and become a dragon rider. Violets body has betrayed her for her entire life and she isn’t even sure she will make it past the first day of her training. She does everything she can to prove herself and survive even when the odds are clearly stacked against her. 

I would describe it as a Harry Potter meets hunger games and it’s perfect for the adult millennial who grew up with those books and want a little more spice.

Speaking of spice, there are two chapters with 🌶️ that can be easily skimmed if needed. If that is a deal breaker, it might not be the book for you! 

I have not had this visceral of a reaction to a book since my beloved ACOTAR and I will be nursing this book hangover for months. according to the author it’s a 5 book series and the second is coming out this November. Get on those pre order lists! Until then I will be irrationally upset that I don’t have my own personal dragon and enjoying my explore page as it morphs into strictly Fourth Wing fan art. 

Well done, @rebeccayarros well done. 

 PS doing more book reviews on my feed like this and it just felt right to start with one that cut deep to my core 😅

⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️💫 4.5/5 (romance)

I would buy anything that Emily Henry writes at this point.  Her books continue to be some of my favorite books I read year after year and Happy Place is no exception. If you are a fan of a good rom com, or are interested in giving this genre a try, I highly recommend picking up this book! 

The story follows Harriet & Wyn, a couple that is seemingly unbreakable, until one day they end things abruptly and part ways.  They decide not to tell their best friends and embark on their annual summer trip to Maine.  In years past, this vacation has always been Harriet’s happy place, a place where she can escape from the never-ending stress of medical school and residency and spend time with her best friends.  She and Wyn decide to lie to their friends about their breakup when they find out their beloved Maine cottage has sold and that this will be the last week they will spend there.  To them, their friends’ happiness is more important than disappointing them with their news.  They only have to fake it for one week, right?!

This book is a classic Emily Henry comedic second-chance romance, there is a ton of back and forth witty banter, butterfly inducing anticipation, and drama. At times I did feel there was a little bit TOO much drama among the friend group, but I was able to look past that given how much I felt like I could relate to Harriet.  There were so many points in this book where I just wanted to hug her and say “girl, I have been there”. 

Save this one for your next beach vacation, or a nice weekend where you have minimal plans and can get lost in this story. 💜

Thank you @emilyhenrywrites for keeping rom coms alive and well. 

Where is your happy place?! Mine is definitely a beach on the east coast in July ☺️

It's almost time for back to school season! 🍎 📚 🚌 

Let's help the teachers in our online community 'clear the list' and get their classrooms ready for the upcoming year.

The 'clear the list' movement was started online so that people can come together as a community and support our educators. All we have to do is help our teachers purchase items for their classroom off of their Amazon wishlist. 
Whether you can contribute $5 or $25, every little bit matters. Even if you cannot financially contribute, if you could please share this list with your community, that helps more than you know!

We have a list of 40 teachers from all over the country that I would like to help this year.  They come from all types of schools and experience levels.  There are urban and rural school teachers, an engineering classroom, STEAM classes, teacher for school for the blind, ESL, special education, counselors, and more.  Guys, these humans are doing incredible things.

In addition to developing a curriculum for the year ahead, many of our teachers are thinking about the supplies they will need for the upcoming year. In most cases, they foot the bill for this from their own pockets.

Let's reach the masses and all come together and use this corner of the internet to pay it forward to our teachers and help them 'clear the list'.

If you are a teacher, please know that you are appreciated and that your kindness, generosity and inspiring work ethic does not go unnoticed here. Thank you for making a difference and being an important influence for our future generations.

Interested in helping us #clearthelist ➡️➡️➡️Head to https://kmmlifestyle.com/clear-the-list or click the link in my profile under my instagram bio.

⭐️⭐️ 2/5 (thriller, mystery)

A whodunnit style thriller from a debut author. I was really excited about getting back into this genre after taking a long break from it but sadly this one fell flat for me.

The story follows four best friends who are invited to a first class bachelorette party in the Caribbean, all expenses paid. They haven’t seen the bride, Poppy, in 10 years, since high school, and despite a long history of broken friendship, she has asked them to be her bridesmaids in her upcoming nuptials.

The girls decide to accept the invitation, why not get a free vacation? They quickly discover they have underestimated their old friend Poppy as they wake up to a particularly gruesome scene after a night of heavy drinking. None of them know who to trust, secrets are revealed, and they discover they don’t really know each other at all. 

While the concept of this story wasn’t too bad (i did find it a little unbelievable), it was actually the characters that dropped my rating for this book. All 5 women were extremely unlikable, which I understand was the point, but their selfishness and offensive remarks made through the book just weren’t it for me. 

Now, I’m on the hunt for an exciting 5 star thriller, any suggestions?!

It’s been a while since I have shared our kids bookshelf! This months theme is ocean and water. 🌊 

We selected books about the ocean, pools, and ocean friends. 

Some of our favorites are Our Pool and Lorenzo the Pizza Loving Lobster🦞

Full list can be found on my Amazon storefront, link is in my bio! Don’t forget to support your local libraries and book shops 💜

⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️💫 (4.5/5) romance

The story follows Elsie, a brilliant theoretical physicist who is living a double life. By day, she is an adjunct professor teaching at multiple colleges in the Boston area and to make up for her non-existent paycheck, she works for a company called Faux, a fake dating service, by night. Elsie has always been a people pleaser, almost to a fault, but this quality works well for her when it comes to charming her clients family and friends. 

Elsie dreams of leaving her double life behind to become a tenure-tracked position at a prestigious research institution.  She can almost taste her dreams coming true when she is offered an interview at MIT to work in the physics department.  That dream comes crashing down in front of her when she finds out that her favorite client’s brother, an arrogant, cold hearted experimental physicist, is on the interview committee.  She is sure that he is going to blow her cover and sabotage her interview.  To make matters worse, Jack singlehandedly destroyed her mentors career and the reputation of theoretical physicists. 

In typical Ali Hazelwood fashion, Jack is a swoon-worthy brooding grump and Elsie writes him off from the very start.  We spend the entire book witnessing the hilarious banter between these two until someone FINALLY admits their feelings. There is definitely some steam. 

I am a forever fan of Ali Hazelwood’s books because, while they are fun and witty romances, the characters she creates are brilliant women in STEM fields and her story plots are just phenomenal.  Not only do we get a great romance from Love, Theoretically,  but she also sheds light to politics within the world of academia and how our main character navigates through this to get what she feels she deserves. 

If you were a fan of The Love Hypothesis, and you haven’t read this - what are you waiting for?! 

If you want to read romance AND want a good story plot, I would recommend this.  There is definitely some significant science terminology in this, but it is easy to navigate through the book. As a former college chemistry major, the nerdy side of me personally LOVES this, but it did go over my head at times.

It’s Friday. 

I have been waiting for Friday all week. It was one of those weeks where, as a parent, you think to yourself multiple times a day…’How am I going to make it through to Friday?’

The answer, you just do. We use all the strength and resources we have and we power through. We do it over and over and over again. 

One day, I will miss these tiring & exhausting days with my kids. Most days there is at least one child glued to me, I change my clothes 6 times bc someone’s food or spit up is on me, I wipe crayon off the walls, clean sticky fingers 10 times a day, and I barely make it to 8pm before I fall asleep. These days are hard, but I know there is so much beauty in them. I am truly in awe of my own children (that they are incredible humans and also by how big of messes they can make 😆)

And now it’s Friday, the weekend we have been waiting for is here. If you are a parent and are feeling this, or maybe you just had a tough week, you made it and you did great. 💜

Also, I have to shout out all the dads and partners out there who make getting to Friday happen too. I know I would be lost without mine 🥺

And yes, K is casually wiping my hair with a baby wipe in that first photo, if you were wondering.

⭐️⭐️⭐️💫 (3.5/5) thriller

It’s New Year’s Eve 1999 and four teenagers are brutally attacked while working the Night Shift at Blockbuster Video. There is only one survivor. 

Fast forward, 15 years later, a similar attack occurs at a local ice cream shop in the same town. Once again, there is one survivor. 

There is only one person the surviving teen from the ice cream shop attack wants to speak with, and that's Ella, a therapist and the sole surviver from the Blockbuster murder 15 years prior.  Ella has spent her adult years in a fog of self-destruction.  Her connection to Jesse, the surviving teen, pushes her to do some digging to find out if there is any connection between the two attacks. 

Ella isn’t the only one looking for connections to the Y2K murder.  We also follow FBI agent Sarah Keller and Chris Ford, a public defender who also happens to be the younger brother of Vince Whitaker, the primary suspect from the Blockbuster case 15 years ago. The story is told from multiple POV’s as our three characters lives intersect on their quest for the truth behind the killings. Is Vince innocent? Was he framed? Is a killer still at large or are they even hiding in plain sight?

This page turning crime thriller will keep you hooked until the very end. I personally LOVED the 90s nostalgia. 

🍿 Speaking of Blockbuster, I have to know what everyone’s favorite 90s movie’s are.  Two of my favorites are Clueless and 10 Things I Hate About You. Tell me your favorite in the comments so I can save them for our next movie night!

⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️ (4/5) contemporary fiction 

Once again, we are transported into the island of Nantucket. In this story, we follow Hollis, the creator of the popular food blog, Hungry with Hollis. Behind the scenes, Hollis’ life seems picture perfect.  However, her life gets turned upside down when her successful heart surgeon husband, Matthew, is killed in a tragic accident the morning after they have a heated argument. In the wake of her husbands death, she grapples with how to mourn the life of her husband, her strained marriage, as well as her rocky relationship with her college-age daughter, Caroline. 

As Hollis prepares for her annual summer trip to her home in Nantucket, she decides to host a "Five Star Weekend”. She invites four friends from each pivotal stage in her life: high school, college, early motherhood and the present.  Each woman invited seems to have their own battle they are facing and we follow them as they navigate this Pinterest worthy weekend that will change their lives forever. The Five Star weekend is a story about love, friendship, and self discovery. 

Like most of Elin’s books, her writing will make you feel as though you are actually there along with the characters. The descriptions of the mouth watering food and luxurious accommodations will transport you right to Nantucket.  Her descriptions of the night life will make you feel like you are dancing along with the ladies at The Chicken Box. If you are a lover of Elin’s books, I highly recommend! Or if you are looking for a book to close out your summer reading, I would suggest picking up a copy of The Five Star Weekend. 

If you can’t get your hands on this book before the end of summer I would also recommend 28 Summers by Elin, which takes place on Labor Day weekend!

THE SEVEN YEAR SLIP 
⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️💫 4.5/5
Romance/magical realism

This book was as sweet as lemon pie. 

At first, knowing this was a romance with magical realism, I wasn’t sure how I was going to feel about this book. I typically like fantastical elements to stay in fantastical worlds, but this book was a delightful surprise. 

We follow our main character, Clementine, as she deals with the tragic loss of her aunt, who was one of the most important people in her life.  She is having a difficult time coping with her grief and she finds herself at a crossroads with her job at a publishing company. She returns home one day to her aunt’s old magical NYC apartment, which was willed to her when she passed, and discovers a strange man waiting inside (I know, I know, just stick with me here). But that is not the only thing that is off putting, the apartment has also taken her back in time 7 years. 

Clementine remembers the stories her aunt told her about her magical apartment, a place that is a stitch in time and takes you back when you need it the most. She is now realizing that her aunt wasn’t just telling stories and the magic inside the old apartment may be just what she needs to help her heal. 

This book was bursting with heartwarming elements of love, whimsy, friendship, family, and FOOD. Seriously, do not read this book while hungry, the descriptions of food were just mouth watering. The character development in this book is also just *chef’s kiss* 😉🤌🏻

Give this book a chance if you have it on your TBR. It took me a little while to be engrossed by it, but after about 50% of the way through these characters and their stories feel like a hug.

REVIEW: VERA WONG’S UNSOLICITED ADVICE FOR MURDERERS 
⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️ (4/5)
Mystery

Nobody spills the tea like Vera Wong. 🫖 

This cozy mystery follows Vera Wong, an aging, lonely, widower and self proclaimed tea-expert.  Unfortunately, her ‘world famous’ tea house is rarely visited. One morning, she walks downstairs from her apartment to her tea house and finds a dead man in the middle of her shop! She calls the police, but is convinced she will do a better job handling this case and starts her own investigation.  The police don’t suspect foul play, but Vera knows there is something unusual about this dead man in her shop. 

Now a sleuth in her spare time, she compiles a list of four primary suspects and inserts herself into their lives to figure out who is guilty.  Vera bulldozes through these four young peoples lives, meddles in their relationships, and conducts a very thorough and well intentioned investigation. Can she figure out what happened to this dead man in her tea shop? 

Immediately upon starting this book, I fell in love with the character of Vera Wong. She is, if nothing else, a mother and creature of habit.  Her antics and routines will touch your heart and have you laughing out loud. The family themes almost overshadowed the mystery piece, but I truly didn’t mind because I found it so heartwarming. 
I really enjoyed the character development and the way the relationships between all the characters played out.  They all seemed to find exactly what they needed from each other in the end. 

I love the comfort and humor in Jesse Sutanto’s writing in this book. It was an easy, fun, heartwarming read and will make you want to run out and upgrade your tea collection. It was the perfect book to kick off a cozy reading season. 

If you are a fan of the Finlay Donovan series, I think you will love this book (and Vera Wong)!

NONE OF THIS IS TRUE 

Book review! 
⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️💫 (4.5/5) thriller

I am so GLAD I finally found a thriller that I could devour in just a couple sittings. I was hooked on this story right from the first chapter. 

The story follows two women, Josie and Alix. It’s starts with the two women celebrating their birthday in the same pub. They cross paths in the bathroom and realize not only are they both celebrating their birthday, they were born on the same exact day in the same hospital. They are, in fact, birthday twins. 

A few days later, the two women cross paths again, this time at the school where Alix’s children attend. Josie discovers through her own personal sleuthing that Alix is a fairly successful podcaster and tracks her down to see if she would be interested in telling Josie’s story on her podcast. She sells it by telling Alix that she is about to make a big change in her life and her story is worth telling. 

After just one interview, Alix has a feeling that there is a lot more to Josie’s story than what she is being told. While she feels unsettled by their interview, she pushes on as she feels this story could skyrocket her career. With each interview we get deeper and deeper into Josie’s complicated and strange life. Alix has a feeling there are even more dark secrets she isn’t telling her and she is determined to find out the truth. 

I feel like that is all I can say without spoiling the story! This book was such a page turner, I had to know the truth immediately!! 

For my audiobook gals, I heard this is great on audio as well. If you have read it OR are adding it to your TBR - let me know in the comments!

Simple Fall Home Decor 🍁 

In years past I would go all out with seasonal decor. I absolutely loved making my house look like a harvest festival.

In this current season of life, decorating my home for fall made me feel a little claustrophobic. While I love seasonal home decor, putting a bunch of pumpkins out that my kids would likely move around 100 times a day seemed a little overwhelming. 

I felt guilty about not decorating for fall yet when it was almost October, almost like I was robbing myself and my family of fully enjoying fall. BUT then I realized that was silly. There are so many more ways to embrace the season. If decorating your home is that for you, excellent. But if it’s not, know that is okay too.

Today I swapped out some faux florals in our dining room and entryway, and added a little basket of pumpkin filler (that my children will no doubt dump on the floor 50 times a day 🤷🏻‍♀️). That’s where the fall decorating will stop for me this year. 

The lesson: it’s okay to change how you embrace seasons year after year. 

What are some ways you and your family celebrate fall together? Top of mind for us is apple picking, pumpkin farms, and baking together ♥️🍂

TOM LAKE

Audiobook Review! 

⭐️⭐️⭐️(3/5) Literary Fiction

I usually listen to 1-2 audiobooks per month, but this is the first time I am doing an actual review.  This book was one of the most highly anticipated books of the year, based on many of my conversations with you! 

This book begs to be listened to.  Meryl Streep as the narrator? Yes, please! I chose this as my monthly audiobook solely based on the narrator and Meryl did not disappoint. 

As far as the story, it fell a little flat for me.  If you aren’t familiar with Ann Patchett, she is a phenomenal storyteller.  I do feel her story telling in this book was excellent but it was the PLOT that I just could not get into. I do wonder though, if my experience would have been different if I read the book versus listened. 

The story takes place in the spring of 2020, when Lara’s three daughters return to their cherry orchard in Michigan. While they are home, they beg their mother to tell them the story of how she met Peter Duke, a famous movie star with whom she shared a stage and romantic relationship. 

Ann Patchett creates this idyllic setting in her storytelling that will make you want to take a trip to Northern Michigan immediately.  Her writing toggles effortlessly between time periods while allowing character growth.  For me, it wasn’t her writing style that fell flat.  It was more that I wanted to see more growth and introspection with her three adult children.  While I KNOW the story wasn’t about them, there were certain periods where they seemed a bit insufferable? It sounds harsh, but I actually think I would have liked this book better if it was just Lara we were hearing from. 

I do highly recommend the audio version, Meryl Streep’s narration is perfection! And if you are a fan of Ann Patchett, it is definitely worth picking up.  The Goodreads rating of this book is 4.26/5, so I wouldn’t take my opinion too seriously!

Have you read or listened to this book? Let me know your thoughts below!

IN MY DREAMS I HOLD A KNIFE 

Book Review! 
⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️(4/5) mystery/thriller

This was the book I needed to get me out of my reading slump! A dark academia mystery thriller set on a college campus in the fall - aka PERFECT October read. 

The story follows Jessica Miller as she returns to her college campus for her 10 year reunion. Over the past decade she has worked tirelessly to rise to the top in her career as a consultant at a highly successful NY firm.  After being passed over time and time again in college, Jessica has one goal for this reunion: to prove to everyone once and for all she’s worth the attention. 

The last time her and her tight knit college group were together, they were mourning the loss of one of their best friends, Heather, who was brutally murdered their senior year and the case turned cold.  The old friends meet again at the reunion, and they are shocked to find Heather’s younger brother is also in attendance and demands justice for his sister. 

The friends are forced to relive the night they all wished to forget and a decade of secrets are revealed. This whodunnit mystery was an absolute page turner and will keep you engaged to the very end. 

I loved so many things about this book, but my favorite was that there were NO PLOT HOLES.  The story follows a non linear timeline, bouncing back between past and present as Jessica and her friends recall the events that happened 10 years prior. Everyone’s story was wrapped up with a neat little bow and kept me guessing until the last chapter. 

This was the first book I have read by Ashley Winstead, and it won’t be the last! This book was highly recommended to me so let me know if you have read it OR if you are adding it to your TBR!

THE EX HEX 🧙‍♀️ 💜 

Book Review! 
⭐️⭐️⭐️(3/5) magical romance

💜 A small town witchy book that light, fun, and sure to get you in the Halloween mood without scaring you. 

Our main characters are two witches, Vivienne and Rhys (poor guy is already has to live up to my high expectations with this name, IYKYK). The story starts when Vivi is 19 in college in the small town of Graves Glen. She finds out her summer love, Rhys betrays her after spending 3 lovely months together. Brokenhearted and sad, she and her cousin, Gywn, get drunk and pretend to curse Rhys for what he did to Vivi. 

9 years in the future, Rhys Penhallow returns to their small town of Graves Glen for their annual Founder’s Day Celebration in October. He is a descendent of the towns ancestors. Once he arrives, some pretty strange things start to happen to him and Vivi realizes her silly ex hex may not have been pretend after all.

Vivi and Rhys have to team up together to figure out a way to break the curse and save the town from corrupt magic. 

💫💫My Thoughts💫💫
It took me way too long to read this book, I chalk that up to starting full time work hours, sick kids, and season changes, but it was a sweet easy seasonal read.  The town of Graves Glen was the winning character for me, it felt like Stars Hollow meets Sabrina the Teenage Witch! 

At just over 300 pages, this is a great option to read the last few days of October if you are looking for a fun witchy themed book.  There is also a sequel called The Kiss Curse! 

Have you read the Ex Hex? What were your thoughts? Share them with me in the comments!

1989 was the first Taylor Swift album that truly spoke to my body & soul. There are some moments in life that you cannot forget. The first time I listened to this album in 2014 is one of those moments for me.

BOOK REVIEW

You, Again
⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️ 4/5 (romance) 

I think I am on the minority of people who actually enjoyed this book 😂 

After reading the reviews, I’ll admit I was a little hesitant to start this but I wanted to give it a fair shot. I’m glad I did! It was unlike any romance I have read. 

Set in NYC, our two main characters are Ari and Josh. Both are young and trying to find their way in their chosen professions as a comedian and chef, respectively. They first meet when Josh is dating Ari’s roommate. They both leave horrible first impressions on one another, but it’s all good because Josh and said roommate eventually part ways. BUT of course over the course of the next several years Ari and Josh continue to bump into one another at random locations around the city. Eventually, they have a meet cute interaction and decide to put their differences aside and become friends. Well, you can probably see where this is going! 

In the author notes, we are told that this story was based on a modern day retelling of When Harry Met Sally. Can these two characters really JUST be friends? 

This book is NOT for everyone. Our two main characters are honestly, pretty unlikeable and self deprecating. At first, I was in the same camp as everyone who disliked this book, wondering how I could possibly finish it.  At around 30%, my opinion changed. Our female main character makes some questionable choices in her personal life and she is very gritty, crass, sarcastic, and has a dark sense of humor. She is the type of character who self sabotages as a terrible way of coping with things in her personal life she doesn’t want to deal with, and at some point I found myself rooting for her to find happiness after self discovery. 

I think that you will enjoy this book if you are a fan of dark comedy. To me the book reads like a movie that would star Pete Davidson and Emma Roberts (in Holidate). It is a great book to read during the upcoming season as the bulk of the story starts and ends with two new years eves. 

Take this review for what it’s worth, but if you don’t like it, don’t say I didn’t warn you 😂😂😂

Jólabókaflóð 📚🎄 The “Yule Book Flood” is an Icelandic tradition that originated during WWII when foreign imports were restricted, but paper was cheap. Iceland’s population was not large enough to support year round publishing and as a result book publishers flooded the market with new titles around the holiday. 

Today, the tradition is still celebrated. The holiday season in Iceland kicks off when a FREE catalog of new books is sent to homes. Exchanging books as gifts is celebrated and over time a new tradition emerged of spending Christmas Eve reading together, often while enjoying some chocolate treats!

How AWESOME is that? I only recently heard of this and when I saw this book in my local bookstore I knew I had to grab it to share with my kids.  I love coordinating celebrations with books and I hope to start a similar Christmas Book Flood tradition with my family that we can look forward to for years to come. 

(Also I got all this info from a very trusted source, google 😵‍💫 so please correct me if I’m wrong!)

IRON FLAME 🔥 

Book Review! 
⭐️⭐️⭐️💫(3.5/5) Romantasy

Let me start by saying that I absolutely loved Fourth Wing. That book consumed my thoughts and became part of my personality after I read it. Iron Flame was hands down one of the most anticipated books of the year for me.

I am so disappointed that I didn’t love this book. I may have held it to too high a standard, but the majority of the book fell flat for me. The biggest difference between this and Fourth Wing was that I could put it down, go days without reading it and feel absolutely fine. 

This book picks up right where the first one leaves off and is a LOT of world building at first. Almost too much? I don’t know, I realized that I have never read a series as it releases before (usually just binge it all at once) so maybe this is a necessary set up for future books in the series. 

I will say, the ending was wild and WOW I mean talk about a cliff hanger. The last 100 pages of that book bumped this rating up a half a star alone. Because of that I will definitely be picking up the 3rd book.  I do think it is still worth reading if you loved Fourth Wing and are committed to the series. 

I have so many thoughts - if you read and want to discuss, my DM’s are open! I know all of us dragon super fans wanted this book FAST but I do hope that book 3 feels less rushed after final edits!

HOLIDAY ROMANCE 

Book Review! 
⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️(4/5) Romance

What a delightful book to kick off my December holiday reading. I couldn’t get enough of these characters and devoured this in 24 hours. This friends-to-lovers story was filled with festive cheer, comedic banter (loved it), travel, and romance. Christina Lauren fans - this book is for you!

Friends, Molly and Andrew live very separate lives  in their adopted city of Chicago, but they come together once a year for their holiday trip back home to Ireland.  Once a year, for 10 years, they spend 7 hours on a plan together catching up on life, jobs, and their string of failed relationships. Molly and Andrew couldn’t be more different, but they agree on one thing, they don’t want to give up their travel tradition.

On their 10 year travel anniversary trip, a crazy storm grounds all flights over the Atlantic for days.  Molly, knowing how important getting home to his family in Ireland is, vows to get Andrew home in time for Christmas. 

Molly’s plan involves them taking every form of transportation, she’s convinced her highly specific plan cannot fail. Along the way, something ELSE happens that Molly couldn’t have planned herself...

A year of growth for our family in so many ways. We welcomed our little guy and our daughter grew up way too fast. At first, it didn’t seem like we accomplished much in 2023 because we didn’t have any vacations or ‘big things’ to look back on. But we did SO MUCH. It was a year of leaning into simple, and prioritizing our tiny humans. It was so hard, so beautiful, and so tiring. I wouldn’t change a thing. I am so grateful for my people & the memories we made this year. 

I am looking forward to 2024 with my little crew and next year, I am going to try to get in the video (and photo) more often 🌟

Here are 5 of my favorite books from 2023! 

Last year, I read so many good books, but these were far and away the stand out reads for me. I recommend each of these books to everyone depending on their preferred genre! 

A quick run down of my top 5 favorite reads from 2023:

romance // Happy Place - this was a controversial 5 star read from me!  I love a second chance romance! This book gave me so many butterflies and I thought about it for days after reading it. 

fiction // Mad Honey - An easy 5 star read for me last year. It is a heartbreaking, emotional, and thought provoking about a mother’s love, the secrets we keep, and being human. It is part courtroom drama, part love story, and has a surprising twist. I also learned a lot about beekeeping, which was surprisingly so interesting! 

non-fiction // How to Keep House While Drowning - I read this book shortly after I had my son and boy, I will tell you I have never felt more seen by a non fiction ‘how to’ book. I would describe this more as a gentle guide to rid yourself of feeling anxiety and shame over the pressure of keeping up with home care and ‘doing it all’. I think at one point I started crying in the car while listening to this because I finally felt like someone was sharing all my EXACT feelings. 

thriller // None of This is True - this was such a page turner! My favorite thriller I have read in years, probably! There is a fun podcast trope that I heard is EXCELLENT on audio. The twists and turns in this book are truly never ending and will keep you on the edge of your seat. True crime lovers - you will enjoy this!

fantasy // Fourth Wing - not sure what more there is to say about a book that became my entire personality in 2023. Dragons, shadows, morally grey characters, academia, romance, what more could you ask for honestly? 

In 2024 I would love to read 50 books! This year I am not going to feel guilty about reading romance and I am hoping to discover more fiction and thrillers that I love. 

Tell me, what are your favorites from 2023?? What are you wanting to read this year?!

PART OF YOUR WORLD

BOOK REVIEW
⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️ 5/5 (romance)

5 stars right out of the gate! I did not expect to hand out my first 5 star review of 2024 so soon, but I couldn’t resist bestowing the honor on this delightful book. I read this in less than a day! So many of you recommended this author and book to me and it surely did not disappoint. This will not be my last Abby Jimenez read! 

If you are looking for a romance with a thoughtful plot, good character development, and minimal spice - look no further. This book is for you and you’ll adore it. This story is about two characters who’s lives could not be more different. We first meet Alexis Montgomery, a ER doctor who has been tasked with upholding her prestigious family’s 125 year old legacy. She has a meet cute moment with Daniel Grant, a small town carpenter and town mayor. Sparks fly immediately and they decide to start a fling as they both know they can’t possibly fit into each others impossibly different worlds (see where this is going…👀).

I truly can’t believe it took me this long to read on of Abby’s books. I have her most recent release, ‘Yours Truly’ on my bookshelf and I am IMMEDIATELY moving it to the top of my TBR. Her story telling is just *chefs kiss*

Thank you to everyone who pulled me out from under a rock to recommend this! (And to my loving husband who bought it for me - which is FOR sure going to remind me of all year 😆)
